44\u3046\u7d4c\u6b74\u3067\u3084\u3063\u3066\u304d\u305f\u300c\u68ee\u300d\u3068\u3044\u3046\u7537\u304c\u30b9\u30c8\uff12\u306e\u30b5\u30ac\u30c3\u30c8\u3092\u4f5c\u308a\u30e2\u30ea\u30ac\u30f3\u306e\u30c9\u30c3\u30c8\u3092\u5236\u4f5c\u3057\u30b9\u30c8\uff13\u3067\u306f\u30a8\u30ec\u30ca\u3092\u5236\u4f5c\u3057\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002\u5f7c\u306e\u9032\u5316\u304c\u521d\u671f\u304b\u3089\u4e2d\u671f\u306e\u683c\u30b2\u30fc\u306b\u304b\u306a\u308a\u306e\u5f71\u97ff\u3092\u53ca\u307c\u3057\u3066\u3044\u307e\u3059}}</ref> <br> [[Shuk\u014d Murase]] <small>(Japanese animated series)</small>\n|origin=[[Scotland]]\n|nationality=[[Scottish people|Scottish]]\n|weapon=Transmorphic wings\n|occupation=Princess of the Aensland House <br/> Queen of Makai <small>(later games)</small><ref name=mc/>\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Morrigan Aensland'''{{#tag:ref|Her last name in the series has been spelled in English as \"Aenslaed,\"<ref name=AT>Keith Busby, ''Arthurian Literature XVIII'', 2001 (p. 250).</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/starlog_magazine-231/starlog_231#page/n9/mode/1up/ |title=Starlog Magazine Issue 231 |publisher=Archive.org |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> particularly in the subtitles of the 1997 anime miniseries ''[[Night Warriors: Darkstalkers' Revenge (anime)|Night Warriors: Darkstalkers' Revenge]]'', where it was occasionally pronounced as such, in addition to the final episode of the 1995 cartoon series.<ref>[http://rq87.flyingomelette.com/RQ/C/DS/13/13.html Everyone's a Critic \u2013 Rage Quitter 87's Cartoon Coverage]. Retrieved 19 June 2014.</ref>|group=\"note\"}}|\u30e2\u30ea\u30ac\u30f3\u30fb\u30a2\u30fc\u30f3\u30b9\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9|Morigan \u0100nsurando|lead=yes}} is a fictional [[antihero|antiheroine]] and the female [[protagonist]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/our-favorite-fanimecon-2019-cosplays-god-of-wars-k/2900-2796/7/|title=Our Favorite FanimeCon 2019 Cosplays: God Of War's Kratos, Overwatch's D.Va, And More|last=Vicencio|first=Chastity|date=2019-05-29|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref> in [[Capcom]]'s ''[[Darkstalkers]]'' series. Having debuted in 1994's ''[[Darkstalkers: The Night Warriors]]'', she has since appeared in every game in the series and in various related media and merchandise, as well as in multiple video games outside the ''Darkstalkers'' line, including in most entries in both ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom]]'' and ''[[SNK vs. Capcom]]''. \n\nIn the series, she is a [[succubus]] and a powerful princess (later queen) of the demon realm Makai, who is very vain and lives for little more than the excitement of battle, but slowly takes more of her royal responsibilities seriously despite her obsessive fascination with the human world. She has a sister-like split part named [[Lilith (Darkstalkers)|Lilith]] and a rival named [[Demitri Maximoff]], and her moveset is reminiscent of [[Ryu (Street Fighter)|Ryu]] and [[Ken Masters|Ken]] from ''[[Street Fighter]]''.\n\n==Appearances==\n===Video games===\n====''Darkstalkers'' games====\nIn the ''[[Darkstalkers]]'' series, Morrigan is a [[succubus]] and the adopted daughter of the demon king [[Belial in popular culture|Belial]] of the Aensland House, one of the three major houses of Makai (\u9b54\u754c, lit. \"Demon World\"), who prophesied her birth in [[Scotland]] in the year 1678. Belial also foresaw the dangers of the incredible power residing in Morrigan. If she could not properly control her power, it would consume her body and the world would suffer catastrophic damage. To counter this event from unfolding, Belial sealed two thirds of her soul away until she can endure her full power: Sealing one third in himself that would return to Morrigan upon his death. The other one third was sealed within a [[pocket dimension]] that eventually became a being of its own, named [[Lilith (Darkstalkers)|Lilith]]. Without knowing this, Morrigan grew up, tended after by two lesser demons named Lucien and Mudo. She found her life as a sheltered princess in the Aensland castle dull, so she would frequently visit the human world to look for entertainment, tempting humans regardless of their sex and fighting for her own pleasure.<ref>DoubleJump, ''Cross Edge: The Official Strategy Guide''. Onionbat 2009, page 18.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.famitsu.com/news/201302/12028596.html |title=PS3/Xbox 360\u300e\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2 \u30ea\u30b6\u30ec\u30af\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u300f\u306e\u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u3001\u201c\u30c7\u30df\u30c8\u30ea\u201d\u3068\u201c\u30e2\u30ea\u30ac\u30f3\u201d\u306e\u7d39\u4ecb\u6620\u50cf\u304c\u516c\u958b\u3010\u52d5\u753b\u3042\u308a\u3011 - \u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u901a.com |publisher=Famitsu.com |date=2013-02-12 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> She is capable of crossing into the human dimension without the use of the gates but simply relying on her own translocation ability.\n\nCenturies later, during the events of ''[[Darkstalkers: The Night Warriors]]'' (''Vampire'') and ''[[Night Warriors: Darkstalkers' Revenge]]'' (''Vampire Hunter''), Morrigan is drawn to a strange immense power (which would turn out to be the alien fire demon [[Pyron]]) and ventures into the human world once again. Morrigan finds and challenges Pyron to battle, but is defeated, as he turns out to be too strong for her to beat. Instead, victory goes to the banished vampire lord [[Demitri Maximoff]], her father's sworn enemy, who absorbs Pyron's power.<ref name=sopitas>{{cite web|url=http://www.sopitas.com/608024-morrigan-aesland-capcom-personajes-videojuegos-darkstalkers-geek/ |title=Una succubus de cuidado: Morrigan Aensland |publisher=Sopitas.com |date=2016-04-24 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> Sixteen years later, Belial passes away and Morrigan is informed she is the successor to the Aensland throne to rule for next 1,200 years. Although she becomes rightfully the ruler of Makai as Queen of the Night,<ref name=4g/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.famitsu.com/news/201605/25106629.html |title=\u300e\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2\u300f\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba\u306e\u30e2\u30ea\u30ac\u30f3\u304c\u5996\u8276\u306a\u30ca\u30fc\u30b9\u30b3\u30b9\u30c1\u30e5\u30fc\u30e0\u3067\u30d5\u30a3\u30ae\u30e5\u30a2\u5316 - \u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u901a.com |publisher=Famitsu.com |date=2016-05-25 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=\u300a\u51a8\u5ca1\u6676\u300b |url=http://www.inside-games.jp/article/2013/02/15/63900.html |title=\u300e\u9b3c\u6b66\u8005Soul\u300f\u5927\u578b\u30a2\u30c3\u30d7\u30c7\u30fc\u30c8\u300c\u56db\u56fd\u93ae\u9b42\u7de8\u300d\u5b9f\u65bd \u2015 \u30e2\u30ea\u30ac\u30f3\u304c\u5c0f\u59d3\u3068\u3057\u3066\u767b\u5834\uff01 &#124; \u30a4\u30f3\u30b5\u30a4\u30c9 |publisher=Inside-games.jp |date= |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> Morrigan still shirks her responsibilities and seeks to continue her hedonistic and thrill-seeking life as before. Meanwhile, Demitri has returned to Makai shortly after learning of Belial's death and challenges Morrigan for the right to rule the demon realm. Morrigan gradually accepted the insistent vampire's demand prior to the events of ''[[Darkstalkers 3]]'' (''Vampire Savior''), with [[Jedah Dohma]] appearing after his century-long nap and creating the Majigen which sucked Morrigan and her castle into it. Jedah freed Lilith who is compelled to find Morrigan, eventually merging back into her as depicted in both their endings.\n\n====Other games====\nMorrigan was the first Darkstalker's character to break-out of the original fighting game series and cross over into the ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom]]'' series. In ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom: Clash of Super Heroes]]'' (1998, remade as ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom Origins]]'' in 2012), not only was Morrigan present, but an alternate \"Lilith-style\" Morrigan was a secret character; in her intro cutscene, Lilith appears and merges with her in a nod to when the two merged in Morrigan's ending in ''Vampire Savior''. In ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom 2: New Age of Heroes]]'' (2000), she is joined by fellow ''Darkstalkers'' characters [[Anakaris]], [[B.B. Hood]] and [[Felicia (Darkstalkers)|Felicia]]. She was later accompanied by Felicia and [[Hsien-Ko]] for ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom 3: Fate of Two Worlds]]'' (2011),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5518024/marvel-vs-capcom-3-will-be-a-living-comic-with-a-deep-story |title=Marvel Vs. Capcom 3 Will Be a \"Living Comic\" With A Deep Story |publisher=Kotaku.com |accessdate=2014-06-16}}</ref> ''[[Ultimate Marvel vs. Capcom 3]]'' (2011),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marvelvscapcom3.com/us/characters/morrigan|title=ULTIMATE MARVEL VS. CAPCOM\u00ae 3 \u2013 Official Site \u2013 Characters \u2013 Morrigan|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141013171347/http://www.marvelvscapcom3.com/us/characters/morrigan|archive-date=13 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom: Infinite]]'' (2017);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/captain-america-and-morrigan-revealed-for-marvel-v/1100-6445962/|date=2016-12-04|accessdate=2016-12-04|last=Makuch|first=Eddie|website=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|title=Captain America and Morrigan Revealed for Marvel vs. Capcom Infinite}}</ref> in ''Marvel vs. Capcom 3'', Morrigan's rival is [[Iron Man]].<ref name=den>{{cite web|author=Gavin Jasper |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/games/darkstalkers/249897/darkstalkers-the-history-of-capcoms-monster-fighting-game |title=Darkstalkers: The History of Capcom's Monster Fighting Game |publisher=Den of Geek |date=2015-10-22 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> She is the playable sole representative in [[Tatsunoko Production]] universe crossovers ''[[Tatsunoko vs. Capcom: Cross Generation of Heroes]]'' (2008)<ref name=ignvs>{{cite web|last=Bozon |first=Mark |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2009/07/09/the-fighters-of-tatsunoko-vs-capcom |title=The Fighters of Tatsunoko vs. Capcom |publisher=IGN |date=2009-07-09 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> and ''[[Tatsunoko vs. Capcom: Ultimate All-Stars]]'' (2010).<ref name=tvc>{{cite web|url=http://tatsunoko.vscapcom.com/cha_morrigan.html|title=TATSUNOKO VS. CAPCOM ULTIMATE ALL-STARS|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403075520/http://tatsunoko.vscapcom.com/cha_morrigan.html|archive-date=3 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Morrigan also acts as the sole playable representative of the ''Darkstalkers'' series in the ''[[SNK vs. Capcom]]'' series' entries ''[[Capcom vs. SNK: Millennium Fight 2000]]'' and ''[[Capcom vs. SNK 2|Capcom vs. SNK 2: Mark of the Millennium 2001]]''; she was joined by Felicia and B.B. Hood for ''[[SNK vs. Capcom: The Match of the Millennium]]'' (1999).\n\nMorrigan has also represented ''Darkstalkers'' in non-fighting games, appearing in the crossover tactical role-playing game ''[[Namco \u00d7 Capcom]]'' (2005)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bandainamcoent.co.jp/cs/list/namco_x_capcom/character/index.php |title=PS2 NAMCO x CAPCOM &#124; \u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc |publisher=Bandainamcoent.co.jp |date= |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> and the multi-company crossover tactical role-playing games ''[[Cross Edge]]'' (2008),<ref>{{cite web|author=AJ Glasser|url=http://kotaku.com/5246243/cross-edge-crosses-the-sexy-line |title=Cross Edge Crosses The Sexy Line |publisher=Kotaku.com |date=8 May 2009|accessdate=2014-06-16}}</ref> ''[[Project X Zone]]'' (2012),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/project-x-zone |title=Project X Zone Review |publisher=Gamerevolution.com |accessdate=2014-06-29}}</ref> and ''[[Project X Zone 2]]'' (2015),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nichegamer.com/2015/08/project-x-zone-2-adds-chun-li-morrigan-alisa-and-more/ |title=Project X Zone 2 Adds Chun-Li, Morrigan, Alisa, and More |publisher=Niche Gamer |date=2015-08-05 |accessdate=2015-08-25}}</ref> in all cases appearing with other ''Darkstalkers'' personalities, as well as in puzzle games ''[[Super Puzzle Fighter II Turbo]]'' (1996), ''Street Fighter Puzzle Spirits'' (2015),<ref name=4g>{{cite web|url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/277/G027771/20150430140/ |title=\u300c\u30b9\u30c8\u30d1\u30ba\u300d\uff0c\u300c\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2\u300d\u306e\u30e2\u30ea\u30ac\u30f3\u3068\u30d5\u30a7\u30ea\u30b7\u30a2\u304c\u671f\u9593\u9650\u5b9a\u3067\u767b\u5834 |publisher=4Gamer.net |date=2015-04-14 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> and ''[[Puzzle Fighter (2017 video game)|Puzzle Fighter]]'' (2017),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jp.automaton.am/articles/newsjp/20170901-53672/|title=\u30ab\u30d7\u30b3\u30f3\u306e\u843d\u3061\u7269\u30d1\u30ba\u30eb\u7d9a\u7de8\u300ePuzzle Fighter\u300f\u304c\u30e2\u30d0\u30a4\u30eb\u5411\u3051\u306b\u6d77\u5916\u767a\u8868\u3002\u30ea\u30e5\u30a6\u30fb\u30e2\u30ea\u30ac\u30f3\u30fb\u30c0\u30f3\u30c6\u30fb\u30d5\u30e9\u30f3\u30af\u3055\u3093\u306a\u3069\u52e2\u63c3\u3044|last=Yamanaka|first=Taijiro|date=2017-09-01|work=AUTOMATON|access-date=2018-07-30|language=ja-JP}}</ref> in a fighting game ''[[Super Gem Fighter Mini Mix|Super Gem Fighter Mini Mix / Pocket Fighter]]'' (1997),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/newproducts/consumer/pocket/chara.html |title=\u30dd\u30b1\u30c3\u30c8\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30bf\u30fc |publisher=Capcom |accessdate=8 September 2014 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100407210211/http://www.capcom.co.jp/newproducts/consumer/pocket/chara.html |archivedate=7 April 2010 }}</ref> in card games ''[[SNK vs. Capcom: Card Fighters Clash]]'' (1999) and ''Street Fighter \u00d7 All Capcom'' (2013),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/10/30/street-fighter-x-capcom-cutest-capcom-mashup-date/ |title=Street Fighter X All Capcom Is The Cutest Capcom Mashup To Date |publisher=Siliconera |date=2013-10-30 |accessdate=2014-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sf-ac.jp/pc/ |title=\u30b9\u30c8\u30ea\u30fc\u30c8\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30bf\u30fc\u00d7\u30aa\u30fc\u30eb\u30ab\u30d7\u30b3\u30f3 \u516c\u5f0f\u30d7\u30ed\u30e2\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8 \u3010\u30ab\u30d7\u30b3\u30f3\u30aa\u30f3\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30ba\u3011 |publisher=Sf-ac.jp |accessdate=2014-05-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417092906/http://www.sf-ac.jp/pc/ |archive-date=17 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in a mobile game ''Street Fighter Battle Combination'' (2015),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/227/G022786/20150414063/ |title=\u300c\u30b9\u30c8\u30ea\u30fc\u30c8\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30bf\u30fc \u30d0\u30c8\u30eb\u30b3\u30f3\u30d3\u30cd\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u300d\u300c\u7b2c1\u56de\u4e16\u754c\u683c\u95d8\u5927\u4f1a\u300d\u3092\u5b9f\u65bd |publisher=4Gamer.net |date=2015-03-30 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> and in a browser-based social card game ''[[Onimusha]] Soul'' (2014).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.oni-soul.jp/contents/collabo/index_f.html#collabo|title=\u9b3c\u6b66\u8005Soul CAPCOM\u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30eb\u30b3\u30e9\u30dc|author=|publisher=|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> With all of her appearances in Capcom crossover projects, Morrigan is the single most common ''Darkstalkers'' cast member to appear outside of the origin series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesvillage.it/retro/news/403144/una-partita-a-darkstalkers-the-night-warriors/ |title=Una partita a... Darkstalkers \u2013 The Night Warriors \u2022 |publisher=Gamesvillage.it |date=2016-05-22 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref>\n\nMorrigan is a playable guest character in the [[Sega Dreamcast]] port of [[Psikyo]]'s shoot 'em up game ''[[Gunbird 2]]'' (2000),<ref>Thomas Wilde, [http://www.gamingtarget.com/article.php?artid=1117 Gunbird 2], Gaming Target, 21 August 2001.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/cheats/games/gunbird-2-dc-14735#4dc02a9a2db5b9541e0002f7 |title=Gunbird 2 Cheats, Codes, Unlockables \u2013 Dreamcast \u2013 IGN |publisher=Uk.ign.com |date= |accessdate=2015-07-16}}</ref> in the North American version of ''[[We Love Golf!]]'' (2008),<ref>Jason Dobson, [http://www.joystiq.com/2008/05/16/ken-and-morrigan-shown-hitting-the-links-in-we-love-golf/ Ken and Morrigan shown hitting the links in We Love Golf], Joystiq, 16 May 2008.</ref> and in the Japanese version of action role-playing video game ''[[Monster Hunter Frontier]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.mh-frontier.jp/topic/payment/premiumkit/vampire/ |title=CAPCOM:MHF\u516c\u5f0f\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8 |publisher=Members.mh-frontier.jp |accessdate=2014-04-12}}</ref> Furthermore, she has her own mobile game, titled ''Osanpo Morrigan'' (\u304a\u6563\u6b69\u30e2\u30ea\u30ac\u30f3 Morrigan Taking a Walk),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/keitai/action/action03.html |title=\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30ab\u30d7\u30b3\u30f3\uff1aCAPCOM WORLD JAPAN |publisher=Capcom.co.jp |accessdate=2014-04-12}}</ref> and made cameo appearances in games such as ''[[Street Fighter Alpha 2]]'',<ref>Morrigan can be seen at [[Ken Masters]]' stage along with Lord Raptor, Hsien-Ko, Mei-Ling and Felicia.</ref> ''[[Capcom Fighting Evolution]]'',<ref>Underworld stage, seen in a portrait on the back wall. The portrait features artwork from ''Darkstalkers 3''.</ref> and ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World: The Game]]''.<ref name=sp>[http://www.ugo.com/games/darkstalkers Every Easter Egg Hidden in the Scott Pilgrim Video Game Trailer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100627000237/http://www.ugo.com/games/darkstalkers |date=27 June 2010 }}, UGO.com, 22 June 2010.</ref> Her collaboration guest appearances in mobile social games have included ''Samurai Kingdom''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gamebiz.jp/?p=214922|title=\u30de\u30a4\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30b9\u3001\u300e\u6226\u4e71\u306e\u30b5\u30e0\u30e9\u30a4\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u30c0\u30e0\u300f\u3067\u300eVAMPIRE RESURRECTION\u300f\u30b3\u30e9\u30dc\u3092\u958b\u50ac\uff01 \u30b3\u30e9\u30dc\u30ec\u30a2\u30ac\u30c1\u30e3\u306b\u300c\u30e2\u30ea\u30ac\u30f3\u300d\u3084\u300c\u30d5\u30a7\u30ea\u30b7\u30a2\u300d\u767b\u5834|website=Social Game Info|language=ja|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> and ''The Knights of Avalon''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gamebiz.jp/?p=223598|title=\u30de\u30a4\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30b9\u3001\u300e\u30a2\u30f4\u30a1\u30ed\u30f3\u306e\u9a0e\u58eb\u300f\u304c\u30ab\u30d7\u30b3\u30f3\u540d\u4f5c\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u3068\u30b3\u30e9\u30dc\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8\u3000\u300c\u8d85\u9b54\u754c\u6751\u300d\u3084\u300c\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba\u300d\u306a\u3069 {{!}} Social Game Info|website=Social Game Info|language=ja|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> among others, and her costume can be worn by [[Chun-Li]] in ''[[Street Fighter V]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gamespark.jp/article/2018/09/18/83867.html|title=\u300e\u30b9\u30c8\u30ea\u30fc\u30c8\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30bf\u30fcV\u300f\u5411\u3051\u300e\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2\u300f\u30b3\u30b9\u30c1\u30e5\u30fc\u30e0\u7b2c2\u5f3e\u304c\u8fd1\u65e5\u914d\u4fe1\uff01 \u30cf\u30ed\u30a6\u30a3\u30f3\u30b3\u30b9\u30c1\u30e5\u30fc\u30e0\u3082|last=|first=|date=|work=Game*Spark \u2013 \u56fd\u5185\u30fb\u6d77\u5916\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u60c5\u5831\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|access-date=2018-11-23|language=ja}}</ref> and by [[Frank West (Dead Rising)|Frank West]] in action-adventure game ''[[Dead Rising 4]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://es.ign.com/dead-rising-4-xbox-one/104584/preview/dead-rising-4-primeras-impresiones-para-xbox-one-y-pc|title=Dead Rising 4. Primeras impresiones para Xbox One y PC|date=2016-06-14|work=IGN Espa\u00f1a|access-date=2018-05-15|language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n====Character design and portrayal====\nMorrigan usually appears as a beautiful young woman with long sea-green hair, usually wearing a sleeveless black [[bustier]]-like top adorned with white feathers and a small heart cut out of the midriff; purple nylons emblazoned with bat patterns; black boots; and conspicuous batlike wings protruding from her back and the sides of her head. She can reshape these wings and her limbs into many forms, including spikes, blades and drills, or even into a [[jet pack]]<ref name=tvc/> or a handheld laser cannon, as well as using them to shield herself from enemy attacks. Her wings can separate from her, forming into an army of bats that can aid her in battle, and her outfit itself is actually made of a swarm of supernatural bats too. She is also able to teleport, to fire blasts of magical energy, and to split herself into two different mirror images that remain her physical forms until joined into one again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Computer_and_Video_Games_Issue_174_1996-05_EMAP_Images_GB#page/n54/mode/1up/ |title=Computer and Video Games \u2013 Issue 174 (1996-05) (EMAP Images) (UK) |publisher=Archive.org |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|This ability was also later used for one of [[Spider-Man]]'s special moves in [[Capcom]]'s ''[[Marvel Super Heroes (video game)|Marvel Super Heroes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Computer_and_Video_Games_Issue_191_1997-10_EMAP_Images_GB#page/n21/mode/2up/ |title=Computer and Video Games \u2013 Issue 191 (1997\u201310) (EMAP Images) (UK) |publisher=Archive.org |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} Her human form is similar, but wingless and sometimes with blonde and not green hair. Morrigan is [[Bisexuality|bisexual]],<ref>{{cite web |author=Gaming Bus |url=http://www.gamingbus.com/2012/06/12/glbt-history-video-games-1990s/ |title=GLBT History in Video Games: 1990s |publisher=Gamingbus.com |date= |accessdate=2016-07-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027104832/http://www.gamingbus.com/2012/06/12/glbt-history-video-games-1990s/ |archive-date=27 October 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> likes to prey on stolen dreams and life essences of sleeping humans,<ref name=mc>{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/video_games/8585/marvel_vs_capcom_2_showdown_spotlight_marrow_vs_morrigan_|title=Marvel vs. Capcom 2 Showdown Spotlight: Marrow vs. Morrigan \u2013 Marvel Heroes Games \u2013 News|author=|publisher=Marvel.com|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=marvel/> and just a kiss can be enough for Morrigan to completely drain energy from her victims.{{#tag:ref|This is evidenced in her ending for the first game, which was cited in Capcom and Gamest's setting essay book ''Mystery of Vampyre''.|group=\"note\"}} Morrigan is 172 cm tall, weighs 58 kg, and her measurements are 86\u201356\u201383;<ref>{{cite book |title=Darkstalkers Graphic File |last=Udon Staff |year=2008 |publisher=Udon Entertainment |isbn=1-897376-04-9 |page=52}}</ref> she often speaks in sexually suggestive [[double entendre]]s and flirts with males and females. Her relationship with Demitri is far from being just antagonistic, and might one day lead to an end of the feud between their houses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/game/content/?p=5515|title=CAPCOM\uff1a\u30ab\u30d7\u30b3\u30f3 \u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30ba \u2013 \u30ab\u30d7\u30b3\u30f3\u4f1d\u8aac\u3000\u7b2c\u516d\u56de\u3000\u5996\u9b54\u306e\u30bf\u30a4\u30de\u30f3\u52dd\u8ca0\u683c\u30b2\u30fc\uff08\u5f8c\u7de8\uff09|website=www.capcom.co.jp|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Morrigan Aensland concept.png|thumb|300px|left|[[Concept art]] pictures showing several design ideas for the character prior to Morrigan's introduction in ''[[Darkstalkers: The Night Warriors]]''. Her designer also created ''[[Street Fighter]]'''s [[Sagat (Street Fighter)|Sagat]] and [[Cammy]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://game.capcom.com/cfn/sfv/column-112432?lang=en|title=ROUND 1: Akira Yasuda part 2 {{!}} Guests {{!}} Activity Reports {{!}} CAPCOM:Shadaloo C.R.I.|website=game.capcom.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>]]\n\nEarly in the development of ''Darkstalkers: The Night Warriors'', the team decided to have two female characters: a catwoman and a female vampire, characters who would become Felicia and Morrigan, respectively.<ref>{{cite book |title=Darkstalkers Graphic File |last=Udon Staff |year=2008 |publisher=Udon Entertainment |isbn=1-897376-04-9 |page=56}}</ref> Initially, Felicia was intended to be the \"sexy\" female character of the title, while the vampire would be the [[kawaii|\"cute\"]] female character. However, Morrigan's design took on a tone that emphasized sexiness, causing Felicia's character concept to be altered accordingly.<ref>{{cite book |title=Darkstalkers Graphic File |last=Udon Staff |year=2008 |publisher=Udon Entertainment |isbn=1-897376-04-9 |page=68}}</ref> The Japanese designers began developing the plot of ''Darkstalkers'' from the very simple stories of only Morrigan and Demitri, whose names have been suggested by the overseas staff for a properly aristocratic feel; their relationship formed the base that was then fleshed out from there.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2013/04/21/video-darkstalkers-developer-roundtable-digs-into-the-fighters-past|title=VIDEO: \"Darkstalkers\" Developer Roundtable Digs into the Fighter's Past|work=Crunchyroll|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en}}</ref> Morrigan's character was originally envisioned as a female vampire; her design was highly masculine, inspired by [[Go Nagai]]'s ''[[Devil Lady|Devilman Lady]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> However ''Darkstalkers'' creator, Capcom USA producer Alex Jimenez, changed her into a succubus because they already had a vampire, Demitri, in the game.<ref name=alex>{{cite web|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/ctf84h/pop-facts-darkstalkers--movie-monsters|title=Pop Facts Video \u2013 Darkstalkers: Movie Monsters \u2013 GameTrailers|author=|work=GameTrailers|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Morrigan's role in the game was to be similar to this of Chun-Li in Capcom's own ''[[Street Fighter]]'' series of fighting games.<ref name=\":0\" /> Her costume mirrors \"her personality: somewhere between a batlike demon and a charming lover.\"<ref name=gs>{{cite web|url=http://uk.gamespot.com/special_feature/marvelcapcom-week7/image-feature/index.html?image=8 |title=Morrigan \u2013 Ultimate Marvel vs. Capcom 3 \u2013 Costume Breakdown, Week 7 on GameSpot |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=2011-11-14 |accessdate=2015-08-25 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111114123902/http://uk.gamespot.com/special_feature/marvelcapcom-week7/image-feature/index.html?image=8 |archivedate=14 November 2011 }}</ref> [[Kotaku]] called her one of Capcom's \"least-dressed female characters\" and \"one of the most [[fan service]]y\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5658417/marvel-vs-capcom-3s-newest-characters-played-by-capcoms-best-fighting-game-player |title=Marvel vs. Capcom 3's Newest Characters, Played By Capcom's Best Fighting Game Player |publisher=Kotaku.com |accessdate=2014-06-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5802126/booth-babe-costume-reborn-as-cosplay-sexy/ |title=Booth Babe Costume Reborn as Cosplay Sexy |publisher=Kotaku.com |accessdate=2014-06-16}}</ref>\n\nMorrigan's character has been voiced in most games by [[Yayoi Jinguji]] until 2011, when the role was taken over by [[Rie Tanaka]]. Morrigan's English voice was provided by [[Erin Fitzgerald]] for ''Cross Edge'' and by Siobhan Flynn for ''Marvel vs. Capcom 3'' and its update. In most of her appearance, Morrigan has had exactly the same 2D [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprite]] set as far as ''Capcom vs. SNK 2'' (2001) as she did in the original ''Darkstalkers'' game (1994).<ref>{{cite web|last=Keil |first=Matt |url=http://www.g4tv.com/games/xbox-360/61912/marvel-vs-capcom-2-new-age-of-heroes/articles/67985/marvel-vs-capcom-2/ |title=Marvel vs. Capcom 2: New Age of Heroes for Xbox 360 \u2013 Preview \u2013 Marvel vs. Capcom 2 |publisher=G4tv.com |date=2009-07-30 |accessdate=2014-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/ssfiv-producers-new-project-is-bigger-than-ssfiv-possibly-darkstalkers/ |title=SSFIV producer\u2019s new project is bigger than SSFIV, possibly Darkstalkers &#124; GamesRadar |publisher=Gamesradar.com |date= |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> As such, Morrigan was featured in ''[[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Records Gamer's Edition]]'' as \"Most reused character sprite in a fighting game\" for her 10 appearances between 1994 and 2001.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Guinness World Records 2012 \u2013 Gamer's Edition|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=115}}</ref> Her sprites look especially poor<ref name=den/><ref>''GamesTM'' 3, page 115.</ref> and out of place in the ''Capcom vs. SNK'' where they got visibly [[Pixelation|pixelated]]<ref>Adam Woolcott, [http://www.gamingtarget.com/article.php?artid=1214 Capcom vs. SNK 2: Mark of the Millennium 2001], Gaming Target, 5 February 2002.</ref> and gained a black outline. She received an updated character model in 2008's ''Tatsunoko vs. Capcom'', which was the first game in which she was featured as a 3D polygonal model.<ref name=ignvs/><ref name=ugo/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://videogamesdaily.com/news/201004/darkstalkers-a-call-to-arms-with-claws-on/ |title=SFIV producer \u2018desperate\u2019 to make Darkstalkers sequel \u2013 and you can help \u00ab Video Games Daily |publisher=Videogamesdaily.com |date=2010-04-24 |accessdate=2015-07-16}}</ref> Morrigan and Felicia were two particularly hard characters to implement in ''Marvel vs. Capcom 3'' due to their constantly changing forms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://videogamesdaily.com/news/201008/darkstalkers-may-be-too-hardcore-for-3d/ |title=Darkstalkers may be too hardcore for 3D \u00ab Video Games Daily |publisher=Videogamesdaily.com |date=2010-08-20 |accessdate=2015-07-16}}</ref> An altogether different [[super deformed]] style design sprite is used in ''Super Puzzle Fighter II Turbo''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Super_Puzzle_Fighter_2_Turbo_1997_Capcom_US#page/n6/mode/1up/ |title=Sega Saturn Manual: Super Puzzle Fighter 2 Turbo (1997) (Capcom) (US) |publisher=Archive.org |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> and ''Super Gem Fighter Mini Mix'', in the latter of which she has an alternative [[Medical fetishism|nurse costume]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Official_Sega_Saturn_Magazine_035/Official_Sega_Saturn_Magazine_035_-_september_1998_UK#page/n53/mode/2up/ |title=Official Sega Saturn Magazine Issue 35 |publisher=Archive.org |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> In ''Ultimate Marvel vs. Capcom 3'' Femme Fatale Pack, which has been also available for free with pre-order from [[GameStop]],<ref>[http://www.capcom-unity.com/brelston/blog/2011/11/11/ultimate_mvc3_costume_blog:_pre-order_pack_edition Brelston > Blog > Ultimate MvC3 costume blog: Pre-Order pack edition], Capcom-Unity, 11 November 2011.</ref> Morrigan received a [[downloadable content|DLC]] \"casual outfit\" costume based on her human form from the ''Darkstalkers'' games and the anime series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/images/898038#0-898038 |title=Alternate Morrigan skin from the Femme Fatale DLC pack for Ultimate Marvel vs. Capcom 3 |publisher=Marvel.com |date=2011-02-15 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref><ref>[http://www.gamespot.com/special_feature/marvelcapcom-final/image-feature/index.html?image=23 The Femme Fatale Pack: Morrigan], GameSpot, 11/16/2011.</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Fahey |url=http://kotaku.com/5823117/are-these-the-remaining-eight-new-fighters-in-ultimate-marvel-vs-capcom-3/ |title=Are These the Remaining Eight New Fighters in Ultimate Marvel Vs. Capcom 3? |publisher=Kotaku.com |date=20 July 2011 |accessdate=2014-06-16}}</ref> Morrigan has several additional alternative costumes in ''Cross Edge''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/blog/sf4/saikyo_blog/2013/03/15_7259.html|title=SUPER STREET FIGHTER IV & STREET FIGHTER X \u9244\u62f3\uff5c\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30d6\u30ed\u30b0|publisher=Capcom|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> In ''Onimusha Soul'', she was redesigned to fit its [[feudal Japan]] theme.<ref>{{cite web|author=Richard Eisenbeis|url=http://kotaku.com/capcoms-heroes-look-awesome-as-samurai-1064767996 |title=Capcom's Heroes Look Awesome as Samurai |publisher=Kotaku.com |date=2012-10-19 |accessdate=2014-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Brown |first=Rodney |url=http://www.nerdcaliber.com/awesome-morrigan-of-darkstalkers-cosplay-by-miss-gidget/ |title=Awesome Morrigan (of Darkstalkers) Cosplay by Miss Gidget \u2013 Nerd CaliberNerd Caliber |publisher=Nerdcaliber.com |date=2014-03-04 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> \n\nThough Morrigan originates from Scotland in the ''Darkstalkers'' canon, neither her first nor last name is of Scottish origin. She is named after [[the Morr\u00edgan]], an [[Irish mythology|Irish mythological]] goddess whose name translates to \"great queen,\" while \"Aensland\" is a nonexistent surname in any [[Goidelic languages|Gaelic language]], and is possibly a derivative or alternate spelling by Capcom of the Scottish surname Ainsley.<ref>[http://surnames.behindthename.com/names/search.php?terms=aensland&type=&x=0&y=0 Surname search: Aensland] \u2013 Behind The Name. Retrieved 19 April 2014.</ref><ref name=\"WRforum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.surnamedb.com/Surname/aensland|title=Scottish: Aensland|publisher=wordreference.com|date=3 March 2011|accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> A nod was made to this by Capcom<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil3/main.html?var1=1&var2=column|title=Devil May Cry 3|publisher=Capcom|accessdate=8 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140908113110/http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil3/main.html?var1=1&var2=column|archivedate=8 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> in their 2005 action game ''[[Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening]]'' wherein a devil woman named Nevan (a Japanese transliteration of \"Nemain\") is able to manipulate bats; in some versions of [[Celtic mythology]], [[Nemain]] was one of the aspects of the Morr\u00edgan.\n\n====Gameplay====\nMorrigan's \"Soul Fist\" special move (a giant flaming skull projectile) is very similar to the iconic \"[[Hadoken|Hadouken]]\" fireball from ''Street Fighter''. She is noted to be easy to use and her \"Valkyrie Turn\" is an especially damaging special move, but is difficult to connect.<ref>''Official Sega Saturn Magazine'' 9, page 84.</ref> Her other specials include \"Shadow Blade\", \"Vector Drain\", \"Shell Kick\", \"Vernier Dash\", \"Soul Eraser\" and \"Darkness Illusion\".<ref name=mc/> \n\n{{quote box|A [[Ken Masters|Ken]] clone? Never!! Morrigan plays nothing like the Raging Red and has many linking specials and EXs. She can link chains, specials, DFs and EX all together for a 40+ hit combos. Cheesy? Not really as it's quite hard to do. One of the better characters with tons of combos waiting to be discovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Computer_and_Video_Games_Issue_189_1997-08_EMAP_Images_GB#page/n109/mode/2up |title=Computer and Video Games \u2013 Issue 189 (1997-08) (EMAP Images) (UK) |publisher=Archive.org |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>|source=''[[Computer and Video Games|CVG]]'' guide to ''[[Vampire Savior]]''|width=30%|}}\n\n''Sega Saturn Magazine'' wrote about Morrigan in ''Night Warriors: Darkstalkers' Revenge'': \"Those thinking that Demitri was the [[Ryu (Street Fighter)|Ryu]] of the [game] should consider Morrigan to be distinctly [[Ken Masters|Ken]]-like, as she imitates [his] Dragon Punch expertly ... Easy to use, and with a Valkyrie Turn that'll inflict more damage than you thought possible (despite being difficult to connect), Morrigan remains a firm ''Saturn Mag'' favourite, not least because of her costume change cheat [code].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Official_Sega_Saturn_Magazine_009/Official_Sega_Saturn_Magazine_009_-_jul_1996_UK#page/n83/mode/1up/ |title=Official Sega Saturn Magazine Issue 9 |publisher=Archive.org |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> ''MAXIMUM'' opined Morrigan is \"a particularly flexible character\" whose \"speed and power will often overcome the toughest of enemies. That coupled with a special attack that inflicts up to 17 hits on its own makes her a powerful adversary.\"<ref>''MAXIMUM The Video Game Magazine'' issue 5 page 84.</ref> According to the ''Sega Saturn Magazine'' guide to ''Darkstalkers 3'', her \"Dragon Punch ripoffs and fast fireballs put her in the Ryu clone corner, but her flight powers, speed and strength make Morrigan the equal of [the game's [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]]] Jedah. More powerful than [[Lilith Aensland|her sister]] and faster than Demitri, this she-vampire is awesome.\"<ref>''Official Sega Saturn Magazine'' 32, page 48.</ref> \n\n''[[EGM2]]'' called Morrigan in ''Pocket Fighter'' a \"well-balanced character,\" having good Supers with \"a lot of hits\" and \"decent\" flash [[Combo (video gaming)|combos]].<ref>''EGM2'' 50 (August 1998), p. 129.</ref> Spanish edition of ''Official Dreamcast Magazine'' opined Morrigan in ''Marvel vs. Capcom 2'' is \"skillful and strong, but doesn't stand out in any way. The Soul Eraser is her best attack, although the rest of Hyper Combos are not bad.\"<ref>''Revista Oficial Dreamcast'' issue 11.</ref> In the original ''Marvel vs. Capcom'', Morrigan calls upon Lilith to perform her Hyper Combo \"Silhouette Blade\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Computer_and_Video_Games_Issue_196_1998-03_EMAP_Images_GB#page/n76/mode/1up/ |title=Computer and Video Games \u2013 Issue 196 (1998-03) (EMAP Images) (UK) |publisher=Archive.org |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> In ''Marvel vs. Capcom 3'', this is replaced by \"Shadow Servant\", where Morrigan a split version of Morrigan copies all of the attacks of the original one.<ref name=marvel>{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/video_games/15113/marvel_vs_capcom_3_showdown_spotlight_dormammu_vs_morrigan|title=Marvel vs. Capcom 3 Showdown Spotlight: Dormammu vs. Morrigan \u2013 Marvel Heroes Games \u2013 News|author=|publisher=Marvel.com|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> She also summons Lilith for her ''Marvel vs. Capcom'' Hyper Combo \"Eternal Slumber\" wherein Morrigan seduces her opponent behind a stage curtain.\n\n===Other appearances===\n====Other media====\nThe 1997 anime [[Original Video Animation|OVA]] series ''[[Night Warriors: Darkstalkers' Revenge (anime)|Night Warriors: Darkstalkers' Revenge]]'' features Morrigan more like her game appearances, portraying her as an idle rich member of royal family who is more interested in going to Earth than in her duties. She would often leave at will out of mere boredom, much to the frustration of her guardians, elder men of the Aensland family. Her father, Belial, is not mentioned. Morrigan's role as a heroine is a focus, with her activities as a succubus downplayed. Princess Morrigan is shown fighting the werewolf [[Jon Talbain]] in the opening of the first three episodes. She seeks to battle the vampire lord Demitri Maximoff when he attempts to return to Makai, but their duel with erotic undertones<ref>[[Jonathan Clements]], [[Helen McCarthy]], ''The Anime Encyclopedia, Revised & Expanded Edition: A Guide to Japanese Animation Since 1917''. Stone Bridge Press, 2012.</ref> is interrupted when they are sensed by [[Huitzil]]. In the final episode, Morrigan goes to Earth after Demitri was bested by Pyron and she encounters him unconscious in the ruins of his castle. Demitri suddenly awakens and attempts to vampirise Morrigan, but she does not resist, much to his surprise. Morrigan tells Demitri that he may become the leader of Makai after all, since a change of leadership is needed to help its current disarray from falling into destruction. They both later observe [[Donovan (Darkstalkers)|Donovan's]] victory over Pyron. The anime's Morrigan was voiced by [[Rei Sakuma]] and dubbed into English by [[Kathleen Barr]].\n\nIn the [[UDON|UDON Comics]] series ''[[Darkstalkers (comics)|Darkstalkers]]'', Morrigan is portrayed as a malevolent, evil and amoral succubus (unlike the games), who wants nothing more than to visit the human world and have a good time, often at the expense of the men she seduces and kills, and completely ignores her duty as future ruler of the Makai Realm. Morrigan's attitude annoys her father Belial and gets her two servants, Lucien and Mudo, into trouble. Eventually she hears of Demitri's restoration, and goes to her father to warn him, only to find that he is in no position to fight. For the first time, she takes on the responsibility that she has often put aside, and returns to the human world to fight Demitri, and prove herself worthy of the Makai Realm and the power that Belial sealed away many years ago. In the special issue ''Morrigan vs Demitri'' it is implied that had Belial not sealed away her power, Morrigan might have evolved into a being similar to Pyron and destroyed the Earth. In the comics, Morrigan's bats are the souls of her human victims, which are not destroyed but remain alive inside her body in an state of eternal bliss and pleasure after she drains them. Aside from consuming souls, Morrigan has no qualms about murdering and taking advantage on humans- despite this, she sees herself as simply taking people's souls in exchange for eternal bliss.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 2005|title=Into the Darkness: The Darkstalkers Comic Book|url=|journal=Play|publisher=Fusion Pub|volume=37|pages=|via=}}</ref> She is also prominently featured in the followup series ''Darkstalkers: The Night Warriors'', in which she, Demitri, Donovan, and Pyron all fight each other. In the later crossover series ''Street Fighter vs Darkstalkers'', Morrigan meets Lilith. Together with her rival-partner Chun-Li, as well as other uneasy allies, Morrigan and Lilith fight and defeat Jedah once and for all, and then they merge, finally restoring Morrigan to her full power.\n\nMorrigan also appears in the comedic ''Darkstalkers'' drama CDs ''Vampire Knight'' (\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2\u30fb\u30ca\u30a4\u30c8), ''Darkness Mission'' (\u30c0\u30fc\u30af\u30cd\u30b9\u30df\u30c3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suruga-ya.jp/product/detail/120035637001 |title=\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2\u30cf\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc \u30c0\u30fc\u30af\u30cd\u30b9\u30df\u30c3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\uff5e\u7279\u9078\u30d0\u30bf\u30fc\u91a4\u6cb9\u5473\uff5e &#124; \u4e2d\u53e4 &#124; \u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u7cfbCD &#124; \u901a\u8ca9\u30b7\u30e7\u30c3\u30d7\u306e\u99ff\u6cb3\u5c4b |publisher=Suruga-ya.jp |date= |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> and ''Dengeki CD Bunko EX: Vampire'' (\u96fb\u6483CD\u6587\u5eabEX \u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suruga-ya.jp/product/detail/120026700001 |title=\u96fb\u6483CD\u6587\u5eabEX \u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2 \uff5e\u30b6 \u30ca\u30a4\u30c8 \u30a6\u30a9\u30fc\u30ea\u30a2\u30fc\u30ba\uff5e &#124; \u4e2d\u53e4 &#124; \u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u7cfbCD &#124; \u901a\u8ca9\u30b7\u30e7\u30c3\u30d7\u306e\u99ff\u6cb3\u5c4b |publisher=Suruga-ya.jp |date=1995-07-25 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> voiced by Rei Sakuma, [[Kikuko Inoue]] and [[Yumi T\u014dma]], as well as in multiple [[yonkoma]] parody comics for that were largely compiled from fan submissions. She is often a lead character in various adaptations of ''Darkstalkers'', such as the 1995 manga anthology ''Dark Angel'' (\u95c7\u5929\u4f7f)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suruga-ya.jp/product/detail/WR3684 |title=\u95c7\u5929\u4f7f(\u30c0\u30fc\u30af\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb)COMICS \u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2\u30cf\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30d2\u30ed\u30a4\u30f3\u30b3\u30df\u30c3\u30af\u30a2\u30f3\u30bd\u30ed\u30b8\u30fc / \u30a2\u30f3\u30bd\u30ed\u30b8\u30fc &#124; \u4e2d\u53e4 &#124; \u305d\u306e\u4ed6\u30b3\u30df\u30c3\u30af &#124; \u901a\u8ca9\u30b7\u30e7\u30c3\u30d7\u306e\u99ff\u6cb3\u5c4b |publisher=Suruga-ya.jp |date= |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> and Akihiko Ureshino's series of [[gaiden]] novels, in particular in 1995's ''Witch of the Crimson Moon'' (\u7d05\u3044\u6708\u306e\u9b54\u5973)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookoffonline.co.jp/old/0012321803 |title=\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2\u30cf\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u5916\u4f1d(\u30e2\u30ea\u30ac\u30f3\u7de8)\u7d05\u3044\u6708\u306e\u9b54\u5973\uff1a\u4e2d\u53e4\u672c\u30fb\u66f8\u7c4d\uff1a\u5b09\u91ce\u79cb\u5f66(\u8457\u8005)\uff1a\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u30aa\u30d5\u30aa\u30f3\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3 |publisher=Bookoffonline.co.jp |date= |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> and 1996's ''Where the Souls Go'' (\u9b42\u306e\u9084\u308b\u3068\u3053\u308d).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suruga-ya.jp/product/detail/2K9454 |title=\u4e0b)\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2 \u30bb\u30a4\u30f4\u30a1\u30fc \u9b42\u306e\u9084\u308b\u3068\u3053\u308d / \u5b09\u91ce\u79cb\u5f66 &#124; \u4e2d\u53e4 &#124; \u30e9\u30a4\u30c8\u30ce\u30d9\u30eb(\u6587\u5eab) &#124; \u901a\u8ca9\u30b7\u30e7\u30c3\u30d7\u306e\u99ff\u6cb3\u5c4b |publisher=Suruga-ya.jp |date=1997-10-29 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> Morrigan stars in Run Ishida's 1996 manga which was published in English by [[Viz Media|Viz Comics]] in two different versions in 1998 and 2000 as ''Night Warriors: Darkstalkers' Revenge'', spending the entire second half of the 2000 tradeback edition fighting Donovan,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 2000|title=Manga Scene: Night Warriors|url=|journal=GameFan|volume=8|issue=11|pages=101|via=}}</ref> as well as in Mami Itou's 1997 ''Darkstalkers/Red Earth: Maleficarum'', a ''[[Red Earth (video game)|Red Earth]]'' crossover manga published in English by UDON Comics in 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-05-22/udon-entertainment-to-publish-darkstalkers/red-earth/maleficarum-manga|date=2010-05-22|accessdate=2010-05-22|publisher=Anime News Network|title=Udon Entertainment to Publish Darkstalkers / Red Earth: Maleficarum Manga}}</ref> and was re-released in Japan in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mynavi.jp/news/2015/06/23/696/ |title=\u4f0a\u85e4\u771f\u7f8e\u304c\u300c\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30d1\u30a4\u30a2\u300d\u300c\u30a6\u30a9\u30fc\u30b6\u30fc\u30c9\u300d\u63cf\u304f\u4f5c\u54c1\u96c6\u304c\u5fa9\u523b\u3001\u7279\u5178\u3082 &#124; \u30de\u30a4\u30ca\u30d3\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9 |publisher=News.mynavi.jp |date=2015-06-23 |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> Hiroaki Wakamiya's 1996 manga ''Victor: Messenger of Doomsday'' (\u7d42\u672b\u306e\u4f7f\u8005 \u30d3\u30af\u30c8\u30eb) has Morrigan use her [[secret identity]] human persona of the biotechnology researcher Professor Mori to study the human world.\n\nIn the U.S. made non-canon cartoon series ''[[Darkstalkers (TV series)|Darkstalkers]]'', Morrigan was redesigned as character and changed into a villain, voiced by [[Saffron Henderson]]. Morrigan's character in the cartoon is jealous, rude, power-hungry and despising humans, especially men. She is implied to actually eat her victims and stated to be a direct descendant of the evil sorceress [[Morgan le Fay]] (with the series' protagonist, an original character named Harry Grimoire, being a descendant of [[Merlin]]).<ref name=AT/> Her appearance was also altered, making her look older and wear a less revealing costume; [[GamesRadar]] commented [[USA Network|USA]] \"gave her a look more appropriate for the [[Wicked Witch of the West]] then a sexy, soul-sucking, battle-loving demon.\"<ref name=\"gamesradar\"/>\n\n====Merchandise====\nScores of various figures and statuettes of Morrigan were produced by different manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myfigurecollection.net/entry/3867|title=Morrigan Aensland|website=myfigurecollection.net|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> These include the figures released by Capcom themselves,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/goods/cfb/news/news_140507.html |title=Capcom Figure Builder &#124; News \u65b0\u7740\u60c5\u5831 |publisher=Capcom.co.jp |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=htt